Drugs now available can put AIDS patients into remission and a vaccine
to protect against the disease is possible, according to a panel of
AIDS experts at the American Association of the Advancement of
Science.

Developing countries may not benefit from new drugs, however, because
they are expensive, difficult to administer and require monitoring,
making the vaccine more important.

The Allergy Institute also reports an epidemic of TB in AIDS patients
in inner cities.  The disease is now increasing after a long decline,
and unlike AIDS, is easily transmitted through the air.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d15"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890302-0063"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="K">   

Drug abusers infected with the AIDS virus should be treated to prevent
TB according to the New England Journal of Medicine.  TB has increased
among people at high risk of AIDS.

The study shows that the TB comes from a lingering infection in a
person whose immune system is weakened by HIV.

People can carry either AIDS or TB for years; most with HIV go on to
develop the syndrome, while only about 10% of TB carriers develop the
disease.  Those with AIDS are more likely to develop TB and infect
others.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d15"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ910304-0002"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="K">   

Incidence of active TB rose 38% in New York in 1990 according to the
Health Commissioner, Dr. Woodrow Myers.
  
The city is responding with tuberculosis clinics and increased funding
for prevention and intervention, including TB testing for homeless,
housing for those found positive, increased preventive measures for
drug abusers and testing for children entering school.

They estimate one million New Yorkers may be infected by the TB germ;
but it is inactive in 99%.  Those at high risk are those whose
capacity to resist infection is impaired, such as those with HIV,
substance abusers, cancer or poor nutrition.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d15"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP900521-0063"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="K">   

TB, until recently declining, has made a comeback.  Health officials
are alarmed by a 35% increase last year in Newark, New Jersey.
Nationwide a five percent increase is attributed to the AIDS virus,
which destroys the body's immune system.

International health officials meeting in Boston last week, alarmed by
the increase in the United States and the epidemic in Africa, urged
doctors and clinics to screen for and treat tuberculosis, especially
in AIDS patients.

Although 10 to 15 million Americans have contracted the TB bacterium,
few will develop the disease; however, a person with a compromised
immune system, such as with AIDS, cancer or poor nutrition may develop
tuberculosis.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d15"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP900316-0028"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="K">   

Federal health researchers find that TB's decline has almost stopped
due to its threat to the AIDS-infected.
 
In 1988, 22,436 TB cases were reported, down 0.4% from 1987.  From
1981-84 a 6.7% drop occurred.

The Center for Disease Control attributes the change to the increase
of TB among HIV infected persons who have AIDS making them susceptible
to illness, including TB.

The TB increase was higher among blacks and Hispanics; both groups
have higher rates of AIDS.

The CDC estimates 10 million Americans are infected with TB, but most
will not fall ill.  115,000 were in treatment in 1987, while 1,753
died of TB.</SUM>

<SUM
