SUMMARIZER="K">   

The tuberculosis rate in American prisons is three times higher than
on the outside according to the Center for Disease Control, who urge
testing, isolation and other measures there.

Large correctional systems in New York, New Jersey and California
report even higher increases in the mid-eighties.  Overcrowding in
prisons puts inmates, staff and visitors at high risk for the airborne
infection.

The CDC recommends testing for new inmates and staff and annually
thereafter, and isolation for confirmed symptomatic cases.

Spread of the AIDS virus may play a role in the TB increase in
prisons.  AIDS weakens the immune system.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d15"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="SJMN91-06276078"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="K">   

Poor ventilation in modern office buildings is causing spread of flu
and other airborne infections including measles and tuberculosis,
according to public health experts.  One office building reported an
outbreak of TB among 40% of workers, traced to one sick employee.

Many modern buildings are sealed to conserve energy, recirculating
indoor air.  Airborne infections may be carried throughout buildings,
infecting workers far from the source.

The amount of outdoor air in such buildings needs to be increased.

Airplanes, waiting rooms, homeless shelters, prisons and hospitals are
likely sites for spreading infections.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d15"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP900215-0031"
SELECTOR="C"
SUMMARIZER="K">   

According to a study in the NE Journal of Medicine, blacks contract TB
six times more often than whites when living conditions are identical,
based on a study of residents of Arkansas nursing homes.  Disease-free
patients at admission were re-tested after two months: twice as many
blacks as whites had contracted tuberculosis.

Prison data also shows a similar trend.

Scientists theorize that blacks originate from Africa, where TB is
rare, while European whites have been exposed for generations.  They
point out that blacks have a similar resistance to malaria, common in
sub-Saharan Africa.</SUM>
